         Once the{Scottish}port for{   
{the shortest sea-route}with{Ireland,} 
 being some twenty-one miles from{     
{Donaghadee}across the{North Channel,} 
 the harbour is now a quiet backwater  
 most of the year,when it is home to   
 the{Aquila Maris 2,}a range vessel    
 working in conjunction with a nearby {
{R.A.E. Station,Portpatrick Lifeboat}  
 and a half-dozen smaller craft,       
 licensed for{sea-angling.}Some pots   
 are set for lobster and crab.         
         The{only non-tidal harbour,}  
 between the Firth of Clyde and the    
 Isle of Man, Portpatrick is popular   
 with yachtsmen in summer and is       
 visited also by motor crusiers from   
 Ireland.Fair holiday weather may see  
 the harbour fill with craft.The former
 lifeboat house now provides a         
 crew-room and a lifeboat museum.
